The article discusses a message from the President to Congress regarding the continuation of the national emergency with respect to persons who commit, threaten to commit, or support terrorism. The President states that the national emergency declared in Executive Order 13224 in 2001 is still necessary due to the ongoing threat of terrorism, particularly in light of the September 11, 2001 attacks. The President believes that these actions pose a significant threat to the national security, foreign policy, and economy of the United States.